.TE
.sp
.sp
The \fImask\fP table allows to select which parameters are part of the fit.
Generally, all keys that take real values can be toggled in the mask.
To enable a parameter group in the \fIelement\fP records, add the respective table name.
Possible parameter groups are \fIhamiltonian\fP, \fIdispersion\fP, \fIrepulsion\fP, \fIhalogen\fP, \fIcharge\fP, \fIthirdorder\fP, and \fImultipole\fP.
Only elements present in the \fIelement\fP table will be included in the fit.
Individual entries can be toggled by adding their key to the subtable.
.SS "Example"
.sp
Settings for fitting carbon and hydrogen parameters, the slater exponent of the halogen atom is kept fixed to starting value.
.sp
.if n .RS 4
.nf
.fam C
max\-iter = 100
damping = 0.1
trust\-rad = 0.1
method = "newuao"
relative = true
script = "./run.sh"
data\-file = ".data"
param\-file = "fitpar.toml"

[mask]
hamiltonian = {}
dispersion = {}
repulsion = {}
charge = {}
thirdorder = {}
multipole = {}
[mask.element]
H = {slater=[false]}
C = {}
.fam
.fi
.if n .RE
.SH "SCRIPT"
.sp
To make the fitting procedure flexible, the module will not attempt evaluate data sets itself but invoke a user provided script.
The user provided script line is run for each fit iteration.
Before invoking the script the module will emit the current parametrization data to the file provided in \fIparam\-file\fP.
After the iteration the module will read the reference data and actual data from the file specified in \fIdata\-file\fP.
The objective function is calculated as root mean square deviation from all entries in the data file.
.SS "Environment variables"
.sp
The script will get information about the current run passed by environment variables.
.sp
\fBTBLITE_EXE\fP
.RS 4
Path to the tblite(1) executable
.RE
.sp
\fBTBLITE_OUT\fP
.RS 4
Name of the data file which will be read by the optimizer to determine the objective function
.RE
.sp
\fBTBLITE_PAR\fP
.RS 4
Name of the file containing the current set of parameters.
This file must be read by the program used to evaluate the tight\-binding method.
.RE
.SH "OPTIONS"
.sp
\fB\-\-dry\-run\fP
.RS 4
Do not run start the fitting procedure
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-copy\fP \fIfile\fP
.RS 4
Write the full representation of the input to \fIfile\fP, all defaults will be filled in and the mask expanded.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-v, \-\-verbose\fP
.RS 4
Increase verbosity of printout
.RE
.sp
\fB\-s, \-\-silent\fP
.RS 4
Reduce verbosity of printout
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-version\fP
.RS 4
Prints version number and citation
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-help\fP
.RS 4
Show this message
.RE
.sp
Command line arguments can be read from an indirect file / response file by specifying the file with @\fIname\fP in the command line.
Each line in the file is interpreted as command line argument, shell like escape sequences are not available.
The file can contain further @\fIname\fP inputs. If the file cannot be the argument is used literally.
